author: Maria Sechi
comment:
The words of Karolina Francov, Donbass writer.

‚ÄúMany ask me why I don't publish anything about what is happening in Ukraine. Why don't I comment and say what I think.



Then I answer. This is not because I feel upset or scared and definitely not because I don't have the courage to speak. And that I don't see the point of speaking. I talked a lot in 2014, 15, 16‚Ä¶ when Ukraine exterminated civilians in Donbass by the hundreds. Indeed, I shouted when the city where my mother lives was bombed, when the pieces of meat‚Ä¶ legs, arms, heads of children and old people were literally scattered on the sidewalks and in the parks. I felt like I was living in hell when I saw the satisfied and smiling faces of my Ukrainian "friends" at the sight of the photos of the corpses ... those of Odessa, those people burned alive. Now. Now I feel emotionally anesthetized. I struggle to be empathetic. I feel embarrassed when friends tell me about the shock and fear they feel, because I don't feel anything anymore. For 8 long years my mother heard the gunshots, howls of bombs and the news of new dead. Donbass people are used to it. All this has become a daily routine. Has anyone prayed for them? Someone of you? Or maybe the American president? Or Europe? Do you know what the people of Lugansk are saying? I tell you: God bless Vladimir Putin and Russia. The demilitarization operation of Ukraine has finally started!

author: Ian Mastin
comment: @Electric Chair  Putin has already stated his idea of Ukranian "independance" is to dismantle the democraticaly elected government and replace it with a series of federal districts and decentralize the leadership of the country turning it into a puppeted extension of Russia. Putin doesnt want Ukraine to join NATO for obvious defensive reasons but he also doesnt want Ukraine to remaine independant for less obvious reasons. Something like 90% of Russias GDP comes from its trade of oil gas and energy, Its been fairly recently discovered that Ukraine sits on several large pockets of oil and gas... now Ukraine cant afford to directly persue these resources so up till recently Russia wasnt worried abou it but when Ukraine started partnering with Western companies like Shell to come in and finance the access to those resources Putin got worried. If Ukraine were able to access those resources by partnering with the west it would become a direct competitor to Russias oil and gas industry selling directly to Europe and being that it has better relations to the EU and NATO than Russia this would futher degrade Russias position of power while strengthaning Ukraines.... Putin will not allow that to happen and Russia can not afford it. This it why Russia targeted Crimea and why its targetting the eastern regions of Ukraine and the energy sector of Ukraine... its about the resources.

author: Leo Alexander
comment: While it may be quite a ways down the road, I really, really hope this leads to some fundamental changes in how the UN functions and addresses international crises. Those diplomats that left in protest when the Russian spokesman Lavrov addressed the chamber shows how utterly powerless the UN is if the best it can do to counter a permanent Security Council member with veto powers is to throw shade their way rather than taking any sort of meaningful action. The UN will never be anything more than a 'League of Nations: Part II' if it has no teeth to back up resolutions. Clearly, if its purpose is the foster peace an prevent war, then it's an abject failure and will continue to be until the most powerful countries are willing to give up some degree of autonomy for their defence to the greater, international community. Ideally, under the circumstances playing out now, the Security Council members would band together, combining their military might, and halt the invasion. Obviously Russia's veto power prevents their actions from even being condemned, let alone stopped; but even in an ideal scenario, direct intervention against a nuclear power is next to impossible short of a world war and potential nuclear holocaust. While the idea of a heavily armed UN might seem hawkish and unsettling, I think it's far less so than the 'might makes right' result of numerous, heavily-armed member states. It can't impact the current crisis, but perhaps if we move in the direction of a UN that resembles a loose confederation with the authority to use a military entirely separate from that of its constituents. Otherwise the organization is an outated waste of time.

author: etinarcadiaego üßø
comment: Btw, if you're wondering why Narva looks so bleak and depressing, it's because today 78 years ago (6 March 1944), the Soviets bombed Narva to the ground. Before the bombings, it was one of Europe's largest fully baroque towns. The bombing of Narva was only the beginning of the 1944 March bombings in Estonia that lasted for a few weeks, and they also targeted the capital city of Tallinn (the national opera, historical synagogue, and thousands of other buildings were destroyed). After the war, when the Soviet occupation began, the old historic buildings were replaced by grey Soviet architecture you see today. The Estonians know exactly what it means to have your cities razed to the ground.

comment:
I sympathise for those suffering in the Ukraine war.  It is terribly sad what has happened.

Part of the blame for the present war situation in Ukraine lies with the West for surrounding Russia with hostile nuclear weapons (NATO) and demonizing Russia.  The West has been pushing Russia to the limit with the intention of dismantling the Russian state with aim to plunder Russia's resources.  The US has depleted its oil resources; the US has now had to progress to low-yield expensive fracking.   With the US economy hugely in debt, the US is now eager to take over the Russian oil reserves and mineral resources.  The present Russian regime stands in the way of US' ambitions.  Whereas detente could have been successful in avoiding the war in Ukraine, the USA has precipitated the Ukrainian war by its US intransigence in recent negotiations.  The main stream media is biased and is conveniently avoiding this issue.  The war in Ukraine could easily have been avoided by detente.

Partial ceasefires always have some meanings. For example, 1) The side that has declared the ceasefire has complete control over the battlefield. 

2) They want to give some rest to their soldiers. 3) They are planning a next level commanding position in negotiations, reconstruction or, once again war is required. 4) They want to open a safe corridor for civilians and foreigners to escape before a new and dangerous attack occurs. 5) They want to improve the supply chain. 6) They want to take the time to bring new units to the border.

author: Muonium
comment: If it is confirmed that these images are indeed from Ukraine's NPP, this is an absolutely unprecedented event in the history of the world. Never before anywhere to my knowledge has there ever been an actual military battle at the site of a functioning nuclear power plant. The only thing that comes remotely close is the anti-nuclear RPG attack on Superphenix in France in 1982 to prevent the construction of the site from continuing - but it was unfueled and thus there was no nuclear risk there. In this case though, the Ukrainians have been trying to isolate their power grid from external sources such as from Russia, in order to maintain it's integrity in the case of attack - given that, they're likely to be operating all available power plants on their grid including the nuclear ones. That means even if the reactors are scrammed the fuel bundles will be producing immense amounts (tens of megawatts) of decay heat which MUST be removed by continuous cooling - if power is lost at the site and backup diesel generators do not function, the core fuel will become uncovered and melt and produce an explosive hydrogen gas bubble just like in Fukushima.

author: DF
comment:
@Butter Robot  no. nuclear fuel has lots of latent reaction heat regardless of whether the reaction is at the sustained criticality of the running state. Once shut down, the coolant needs to be circulated constantly for a very long time. Even storage pools for spent fuel removed from a reactor during refueling remains in a coolant pond for years.
And no, the reactor is not state of the art. Most PWRs or BWRs (at least in the US) are only rated for a direct ballistic (re: plane) crash of a non-modern mass. 737max and. larger all came after such designs.

author: Gdggfv Ghbvbbh
comment: Zaporizhzhia there were 2,204 tons of high level spent fuel ‚Äì 855 tons of which were in highly vulnerable spent fuel pools. Without active cooling, they risk overheating and evaporating to a point where the fuel metal cladding could ignite and release most of the radioactive inventory.The nuclear reactor buildings of Zaporizhzhia have a concrete containment protecting both the reactor core, its cooling system and the spent fuel pool. However, such containment cannot withstand the impact of heavy munitions lead to a further cascade of the other reactors and fuel pools, each spreading large quantities of radioactivity into different wind directions over several weeks. It could make a large part of Europe, including Russia, uninhabitable for at least many decades and over a distance of hundreds of kilometres,

author: IAMGiftbearer
comment: @Mad Mick  Putin is the lunatic. Let's be clear. Ukraine didn't ask for this slaughter. It's an unfair fight. Zelenski is being realistic. He's not being hysterical. It's easy for others to view it that way from their cozy, safe livingrooms, but when you're under attack your survival instinct kicks in. It's not an overreaction. Think about this rationally, logically. How long do you really think they can fight this alone? The Russian army vastly outnumbers the Ukrainian army. Be under no illusions. Putin will move further than Ukraine if given the opportunity. He hates NATO and Ukraine is surrounded with NATO countries throughout Eastern Europe. People need to throw away the false belief that staying out of this will save themselves, because Putin is not rational and he takes ANY resistance, even humanitarian aid to the other side as a threat (because he is a paranoid person to begin with). His end game is world domination. Are you really willing to give it to him? You can't treat this like a controlled burn as in a wildfire. People like Putin do not just burn themselves out. The more ground they take, the more emboldened they get. The world will eventually have to face this reality and step up to the plate.

Even if Ukraine is brought to its knees n in our opinion it means God has not done anything or He has failed to protect Ukraine n we only see it as the "end" but does it mean the "end" to God? God doesn't work His ways according to our plan, desire or even prayers. Ultimately it is always His Will that matters. Like Jesus praying "if it be possible please remove this cup but NOT MY WILL BUT YOUR WILL BE DONE" n those of us familiar with this biblical account will know that Jesus prayer was "not answered", "God didn't save Jesus as Jesus has prayed for" n so Jesus went to the cross to die for our sins so that we can have a relationship with God our creator again no longer separated by sin. We would have say the same thing of God "so what has God done? Nothing right? Cos Jesus was crucified on the cross n God has not done anything to save Jesus".
